t, and assesses that achievement within the context of an array of major literary figures from Montaigne to Seamus Heaney and Wallace Stevens. R. S. Thomas: Identity, environment, deity proves invaluable as a beginner's introduction to the Welsh poet, as a student's guide to critical thinking about the poet's work, and as a provocative new step in scholarly studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature and sciencezWales. 0aReligious poetry, Welsh. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aThomas's oeuvre.  aThomas's poetry.  aapplied technology.  adeity.  aenvironment.  aidentity.  amodern physics.  anatural world.  areconfiguring.  areligious poetry.  ascience.  aspiritual experience.  atheology of experience.  atheology of nature mysticism.1 aMorgan, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137616zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137616zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526137616/original  a978-3-11-128363-0 Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA